The {{ill|Boshin War|ja|戊辰戦争|12=draft|12=draft}}, which started with the {{ill|Battle of Toba–Fushimi|ja|鳥羽・伏見の戦い|12=draft|12=draft}} and eventually spread nationwide, also turned Niigata City into a fierce battlefield. Many lives were lost on both sides: the Western Army (new government forces from {{ill|Satsuma Domain|ja|薩摩藩|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Chōshū Domain|ja|Chōshū Domain|12=draft|12=draft}}, etc.) and the Eastern Army ({{ill|Yonezawa Domain|ja|米沢藩|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Aizu Domain|ja|Aizu Domain|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Shōnai Domain|ja|庄内藩|12=draft|12=draft}}). In October 1868 (Meiji 1), a monument for the Western Army war dead was established in Tokiwagaoka (former site of {{ill|Niigata University|ja|新潟大学|12=draft|12=draft}} headquarters), and the shrine was built to enshrine 416 deities of the Boshin War's government forces as Niigata Shōkonsha. In 1875 (Meiji 8), it was renamed to Kankai Shōkonsha{{sfn|新潟市|1996}}.

In July 1941 (Shōwa 16), it was renamed to Gokoku Shrine by Ministry of Home Affairs ordinance. There was intense competition to host the shrine among Niigata City, {{ill|Shibata, Niigata|ja|新発田市|12=draft|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Takada, Niigata|ja|高田市|12=draft|12=draft}}. In 1941 (Shōwa 16), Niigata City was chosen{{sfn|新潟市|1996}}.

From June 1942 (Shōwa 17), relocation to Nishifunamimachi began, and by May 1945 (Shōwa 20), the relocation was completed with the mobilization of 25,000 people{{sfn|新潟市|1996}}.

In 1985 (Shōwa 60), 92 sets of remains believed to be from the Eastern Army war dead were discovered at the former Niigata University headquarters site, and they were reburied in the "Boshin War Martyrs Cemetery" within the Gokoku Shrine grounds. In 1987 (Shōwa 62), the "Boshin War Eastern Army Memorial" was erected.

